media.alt:
Bushra, 7, is the sole survivor of a bomb blast that destroyed her home and killed her immediate family. 

She doesn’t like to talk a lot, and is never without her stuffed toy “rabbit,” who traveled with her to Lebanon from Syria. It is the only possession she has from home. 

Bushra doesn’t like to go outside – the only time she leaves her apartment building is when she travels to and from school with her best friend. She feels strongest when she’s learning at school, where she forgets to be sad. 

See more: http://cnn.it/facesofsyria

Every time Omar moves, he puts all his things in a small backpack that he carries himself. 

His family first fled Syria for Egypt, and then moved to Turkey in search of work. Next month the four-year-old will move to Norway, where his father has gained residency.

Because Omar has moved so much in the past five years, he’s had to learn new languages so people can understand him – and he’s become very good at making new friends, he says. 

When he grows up, he wants to own a phone so he can talk to his family in Syria.

See more: http://cnn.it/facesofsyria

Chindar is 13 and the eldest son in his family. He’s illiterate like his parents, and doesn’t go to school in Jordan because he doesn’t like how he’s treated by the teacher and other pupils. 

His family of five lives on $10 per person per month, which they receive from World Food Program. Everything they eat and need must be subtracted from this sum. 

The only objects Chindar owns just for himself are marbles -- he has a jar full of them because he is a good player and always wins. 

See more: http://cnn.it/facesofsyria

Growing up in war means that Lamees has lived a very different life to that of her older two siblings. 

In Damascus, their lives were filled with constant socializing with friends and family. But living in a foreign town in Jordan where they do not feel safe has meant Lamees, 3, lives a very confined life. 

At a child-friendly center in town, Lamees has learned that she is a “good drawer” and very good at making friends. She likes to pose for selfies, and wants to go to the center every day to meet new friends. 

See more: http://cnn.it/facesofsyria

Hanine was in middle school in Damascus when the war started. Now 17, she works in a pastry shop in Lebanon. 

“I became stronger,” she says. “I feel that I lost my femininity. I’m not the girl who takes care of how she looks, or puts on make-up anymore. I don’t think about things like this at all now. I forgot Hanine, the girl. I have become more practical. I am Hanine the laborer now.” 

Today, Hanine is the sole breadwinner in her family. But she doesn’t plan on staying in Lebanon for long.

“In five years, I won’t be here,” she says. “I will be in Europe. I hope that I’ll be either a college student studying engineering, or graduated by then.” 

See more: http://cnn.it/facesofsyria

At 16, Hussam says he became a man sometime in the last five years.

All he thought of when he was 11 and living in Syria was playing football. Now at a refugee camp in Jordan, he says everything is important, and he notices everything around him.

He says he is the best version of himself yet -- and for the first time in a long time, life is stable and he is able to plan his future.

See more: http://cnn.it/facesofsyria

Nirous is 8 and wants to be a teacher someday. Her family currently lives in Greece and hopes to make their way to Germany.

“If I can go back, I would want to see my cousin,” Nirous says. But her mother says that after they left Syria, her cousin died when bombs destroyed their house.

See more: http://cnn.it/facesofsyria

“When I was in Syria, I didn’t worry about anything,” says Mohammad, 17. 

Today he works at a vegetable market in Lebanon – and he says he felt a change right away.

“I got depressed, and started worrying about things I knew that a boy my age shouldn’t worry about,” he says. “Sometimes I would sit by myself, remember my friends in Syria and just cry.”

The first person Mohammad wants to see if he goes back to Syria is his cousin. “She was my best friend,” he says. “I would tell her that I miss her so very much. The war changed both of us a lot.” 

See more: http://cnn.it/facesofsyria

Raheem, 11, doesn’t like to complain. But he wishes he could be alone more. Sharing a cramped shelter with nine other family members in Lebanon is hard. 

“In the camp everyone is everywhere all the time,” he says. “In Syria I had my bike. I’d ride with my friends every day, to school and around. … If I had my bike I would ride to the ocean. I can see the ocean -- but I have never been there.” 

Every day, he tries to help his mother look after his younger siblings. He tries to do everything for himself so he is not a problem for his mother. 

In the future he wants to be a lawyer so he can help people know their rights – especially refugees.

See more: http://cnn.it/facesofsyria
